/ul>\r\n\r\n<p>MelaNostrum is a collaboration between researchers and clinicians from Mediterranean countries - Italy, Spain, Greece, and Cyprus, - and the U.S. National Cancer Institute. Participants from clinical centers and universities have provided biospecimens and data from detailed questionnaires and clinical examinations, creating a rich, growing database for research on melanoma.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Interested in joining or carrying out research with the MelaNostrum Consortium? See our policy for scientific collaboration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11px\">\"MelaNostrum\" is derived from the Latin \"Mare Nostrum\", which literally means \"Our Sea\" and refers to the Mediterranean Sea. This phrase gets at the heart of what the Consortium represents - a study for all people of the Mediterranean region who are open to share ideas, data, and expertise with others.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11px\">Our logo merges the history and culture of the Mediterranean region with the science of the Consortium. The image evokes a sea wave and the design of Roman columns, which are composed of small blocks like cells of the body. Together we are fighting the black brick representing melanoma.</span></p>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2462:\"<h1 class=\"rtecenter\">MelaNostrum studies genetic, environmental and clinical features of melanoma risk and progression in Mediterranean populations.</h1>\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://fr-s-cbt-devops.ncifcrf.gov:8090/sites/default/files/melanostrum-headerImage_0.jpg\" style=\"height:248px; width:1006px\" /></p>\n<p>People of Mediterranean descent are thought to be at low risk of developing melanoma due to their relatively dark pigmentation. For this reason, Mediterranean populations have been underrepresented in studies of melanoma. This has left many questions about disease development and the characteristics of melanoma-prone families in this region. The MelaNostrum Consortium was established in 2017 to investigate the unanswered questions about melanoma risk factors in Mediterranean populations.</p>\n<ul><li><strong>The goals of MelaNostrum are:</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Identify novel genetic, environmental and phenotypic features associated with melanoma risk.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Molecularly classify melanoma and its precursor lesions to investigate disease development and clinical outcomes.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Study the role of genetics and immunity in melanoma progression and response to treatment</strong></li>\n</ul><p>MelaNostrum is a collaboration between researchers and clinicians from Mediterranean countries - Italy, Spain, Greece, and Cyprus, - and the U.S. National Cancer Institute. Participants from clinical centers and universities have provided biospecimens and data from detailed questionnaires and clinical examinations, creating a rich, growing database for research on melanoma.</p>\n<p>Interested in joining or carrying out research with the MelaNostrum Consortium? See our policy for scientific collaboration.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11px\">\"MelaNostrum\" is derived from the Latin \"Mare Nostrum\", which literally means \"Our Sea\" and refers to the Mediterranean Sea. This phrase gets at the heart of what the Consortium represents - a study for all people of the Mediterranean region who are open to share ideas, data, and expertise with others.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11px\">Our logo merges the history and culture of the Mediterranean region with the science of the Consortium. The image evokes a sea wave and the design of Roman columns, which are composed of small blocks like cells of the body. Together we are fighting the black brick representing melanoma.</span></p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:16:\"field_page_image\";a:0:{}s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:1:{i:0;s:13:\"foaf:Docum